</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 94 / Floating gilt targets investor uncertainties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of England's decision to launch a floating rate government bond -
its first such issue in 15 years - may be seen as an opportunistic move,
given the difficult conditions in financial markets.
The gilt-edged, European government and US Treasury bond markets have all
experienced sharp price falls since February 4, when the US Federal Reserve
hitched up short-term interest rates.
The bond markets have been especially nervous about US inflation prospects
and the possibility of further rises in US interest rates, and there has
been heavy selling of bonds by investors, particularly the US-based hedge
funds.
A few borrowers have responded to the uncertainty over interest rate
movements this year by issuing floating-rate notes, either in US dollars or
in sterling, in order to attract investors.
Some gilt analysts pointed out that the Bank is probably hoping to take
advantage of investor uncertainty about the direction of UK interest rates,
adding that as some of the existing floating-rate sterling issues mature
this year, there will be a shortage of such notes.
One analyst said: 'Some investors clearly think that UK interest rates may
have bottomed out or be close to their lows, and that a floating-rate bond
would enable them to take advantage of a rising interest rate scenario.'
The Bank has been looking at ways of encouraging banks and building
societies to increase the size of their gilt holdings, and it expects its
new floating-rate gilt to appeal to this particular class of investor. The
fact that the new gilt issue is targeted at banks and building societies may
also help - indirectly - to iron out the sharp fluctuations in money market
interest rates.
As part of its regular money market operations, the Bank holds fortnightly
sale and repurchase operations - known as repos - whereby the banks borrow
money from the Bank at a specified rate using their gilt holdings as
security. In theory, by boosting the financial institutions' holdings of
gilts, there should be more government bonds available for use in the repo
operations.
The last time the Bank issued bonds with a variable interest rate, the
exercise was not deemed a success. It sold three issues, of Pounds 400m
each, in 1977 and 1979, which matured in 1981, 1982 and 1983. Demand was
poor and was not helped by the coupon-setting mechanism which was seen as
too complicated. It was set retrospectively, based on an average for the UK
Treasury bill rate over the previous six months.
</TEXT>
