<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / Czech government to pay compensation to WWII persecution
victims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   Bratislava
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Czech government will pay Kcs1bn (Pounds 22.5m) to an estimated 10,000
victims of Nazi persecution during the second world war. However, the
compensation will apply only to those who suffered in concentration camps
and prisons, not to those uprooted and subjected to forced labour. The
government continues seeking compensation from Germany. Six Turkish MPs,
representing radical Kurdish groups, were charged yesterday and could face
the death penalty if convicted for offences against the unity of the state.
Mrs Tansu Ciller, the prime minister, said the MPs were surrounded by a
'cloud of terrorism' which linked them to the outlawed Kurdish Workers'
party.
The Slovak parliament yesterday called general elections in the autumn
following the ousting the Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar in a no-confidence
vote. The vote for new elections on September 30 and October 1, a year and
half ahead of schedule, was unexpectedly unanimous after Mr Meciar dropped
his call for a June poll. On Wednesday an interim broad coalition government
headed by Foreign Minister Jozef Moravcik was installed.
