<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / Rifkind studies plan to lease army vehicles
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the defence secretary, is considering a scheme by which
the army could lease lorries and Land Rovers as a means of making savings to
the already hard-pressed military budget.
The proposal to lease non-fighting vehicles is one of the main options being
considered in Front Line First, a Ministry of Defence study of the costs of
providing military support services which is near completion.
No final decision has been taken on whether to go ahead with the leasing
plan. However, the government has not ruled out the possibility of extending
the leasing principle to fighting equipment in the longer term.
Mr Rifkind floated the idea of leasing lorries in an interview in today's
Daily Telegraph.
The defence secretary told the paper: 'The armed forces buy huge amounts of
vehicles. Nobody in the private sector buys them - they lease. British Rail
is now leasing rolling stock - the same amount of capital will go a lot
further.'
He added: 'Why not do this in the armed forces? The operational commander
could not give a dam if he is leasing equipment.' On the principle of
extending the principle to fighting equipment, he said: 'I would not rule it
out.'
Mr Rifkind is under pressure to introduce cost savings in the defence sector
following last November's Budget in which the MoD was forced to incur some
of the largest cuts of any Whitehall department.
In the wake of the Budget ministers emphasised that the spending cuts would
not result in a reduction in Britain's front-line forces.
The Front Line First studies include proposals to reform a number of other
areas of equipment supply.
There are plans, for example, to introduce more flexible production lines
which could ensure that materials and parts are supplied at a time when they
are needed rather than holding huge quantities of goods in reserve.
</TEXT>
