FT  18 MAR 94 / World Trade News: Iran scraps visas for free zones
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TEHRAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Iran has scrapped visa requirements for foreigners visiting its free-trade
zones, according to a senior official, Reuter reports from Tehran.
Mr Morteza Alviri, head of the high council of free zones, said that under
newly-approved regulations foreigners could stay in the three zones without
visas for up to two weeks.
They would need police permission to stay longer or to travel to the rest of
the country, Mr Alviri added. His comments were reported by Hamshahri
newspaper.
The zones - Kish island in the Gulf, Qeshm island in the Hormuz Strait and
Chahbahar on the Gulf of Oman - were set up in 1989 to promote foreign
investment, export-oriented industries and trade.
Critics in parliament opposed easing of entry regulations for the zones,
saying it would create security problems along the country's main sea
routes.
