</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The prospect of the first big hostile bid for a US fund management-based
company moved a step closer yesterday as the board of Kemper voted
unanimously to reject a Dollars 2.2bn bid from GE Capital.
Directors of the Chicago-based fund management, insurance and broking
company were meeting three days after GE Capital, the financial services arm
of General Electric, first publicised its interest in an acquisition.
Mr David Mathis, Kemper chairman and chief executive, accused GE of trying
to 'steal Kemper with a 'low ball' proposal'. Shareholders would benefit
more from 'providing current management with the opportunity to realise
Kemper's potential,' he added.
The comments, contained in a letter to Mr Jack Welch, chairman of GE, which
was released after the meeting, echo Kemper's earlier rejection of the
uninvited advances.
GE replied: 'We will have a definitive response and will make it at the time
of our choosing.'
