<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / Riot police oust Vladivostok's mayor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The elected mayor of Russia's far eastern city of Vladivostok was forcibly
removed from office by riot police yesterday after a raid on his office.
The move, officially described as the culmination of an investigation into
allegations of corruption, brings to the surface simmering disputes over
reform policies in a city where the growth of a free economy has been more
marked than in any other in Russia, but where the state factories which
provide the bulk of employment fear collapse and where some of the highest
votes for the ultra-nationalist and communist parties were cast at the
parliamentary elections last December.
Mr Victor Cherepkov, elected mayor last year, was removed from the mayoral
building early yesterday by 50 riot police - though later reports say he was
not imprisoned and a local television report showed him lying on a bed after
'suffering a heart attack'. The deputy mayor, Mr Vladimir Gilgenberg, was
carried out of the building, according to the Tass news agency.
Mr Cherepkov, a former submarine captain, has been charged with bribery,
according to Mr Veniamin Chichayev, an aide to the regional prosecutor. Mr
Cherepkov has denied the corruption charges and says political enemies have
been trying to remove him before next Sunday's elections to the regional
legislature.
Mr Sergei Filatov, chief of staff to President Boris Yeltsin, told Tass in
Moscow that the mayor had barricaded himself in his office and surrounded
himself by armed men. 'It seems his supporters were following the example of
the White House rebels,' he said, referring to the battle around parliament
last October.
Vladivostok's stock market, the most active in Russia, has boomed in recent
months - by trading shares in privatised companies. The city has led the
country in privatising its enterprises but, in doing so, has appeared to
trigger a reaction from the state plant directors who see their power base
eroding and from workers who fear unemployment.
Mr Cherepkov has been feuding for months with the Moscow-appointed governor
of the Maritime Territory, Mr Yevgeny Nazdrazenko - who initiated the
allegations of corruption. Mr Nazdrazenko yesterday appointed Mr Konstantin
Tolstoshin, the unsuccessful candidate in last year's mayoral race, as
acting mayor.
Local businessmen and diplomats had viewed Mr Cherepkov as more reformist
than Mr Nazdrazenko, a former factory director whose appointment the
business community regarded as a set-back for market reforms in Vladivostok.
Mr Nazdrazenko became governor of the Maritime Territory after Mr Boris
Yeltsin ousted his predecessor, Mr Vladimir Kuznetsov. Mr Kuznetsov is a
hero to local businessmen, who credit him with initiating the region's
pioneering privatisation of large enterprises. But Mr Kuznetsov's advocacy
of far-sweeping local autonomy put him at loggerheads with Mr Yeltsin, who
sacked him and replaced him with the more loyal Mr Nazdrazenko.
The dramatic attack on Mr Cherepkov appears to be a continuation of Mr
Nazdrazenko's, and Mr Yeltsin's, efforts to consolidate their hold on one of
Russia's most economically dynamic, but potentially separatist, regions.
Vladivostok, the base for the Russian Pacific fleet, was a closed city until
two years ago. Close to the Chinese border, its economy has been buoyed by
trade with its huge neighbour.
</TEXT>
