<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Philadelphia Fed data provide
some support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Advancing technology stocks pushed the Nasdaq small-capitalisation market to
record heights yesterday. Meanwhile, blue chip issues on the New York SE
picked up after a mid-morning setback to post gains on the day, writes Frank
McGurty.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 16.99 ahead at 3,865.14, while the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 added 1.47 at 470.89. In the secondary markets, the
American SE composite inched 0.81 up to 470.63. The Nasdaq composite was a
solid 4.86 ahead at 803.85, well above the all-time closing high of 800.47
set on January 31. NYSE volume came to 303.9m shares.
Equity prices moved steadily ahead in early trading, supported by comforting
data from the Federal Reserve of Philadelphia. Its March business outlook
survey showed a moderating growth trend in the region, and a significant
decline in prices paid by manufacturers.
The news set off a flurry of buying in the benchmark 30- year Treasury bond,
which had rebounded in the previous two days on a series of data suggesting
inflation was in check.
But the long bond's rally could not be sustained. As a result, equities gave
back most of the morning's modest gains. The second turning point came in
the early afternoon, when the blue chips moved forward ahead of today's
'triple witching' expiration of stock options and futures.
The Nasdaq remained in positive territory all day, largely on the strength
of computer stocks. Lotus Development surged Dollars 5 3/4 to Dollars 85 1/2
on announcing a marketing and development agreement with AT&amp;T.
Dow component Caterpillar jumped Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 119 1/2 . The
heavy equipment maker said it would rehire 1,000 workers because of better
than expected demand for its products.
AMR, parent of American Airlines, shed Dollars 1 to Dollars 63 after warning
that it expected a loss greater than Wall Street's estimate of 24 cents a
share. UAL, United Airline's parent, retreated Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 129
1/4 amid uncertainty on the prospects of a proposed employee buyout.
Brazil
Shares in Sao Paulo closed one per cent down after volatile trading awaiting
the outcome of Brazil's debt talks with foreign creditor banks and amid
caution about congressional talks over the government's economic plan.
The Bovespa index, after touching 13,625 and 14,400, ended at 13,938, off
146 points on the day. On Wednesday the index rose 4.2 per cent.
Canada
Continued buoyancy in base metal and energy shares helped to take Toronto to
another strong close, in spite of turmoil in Canadian debt markets. The
Canadian dollar tumbled sharply, pressuring bonds but assisting Toronto
commodity shares. The TSE 300 index added 17.6 at 4,543.3 and rises led
falls by 475 to 331 after volume of 78.1m shares.
</TEXT>
