<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / World Commodities Prices: Wool
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Australian wool sold well again this week, and the overall market indicator
finished another 8 cents higher at a new seasonal peak of 554 cents a kg.
New Zealand was also a firm market, with some wools dearer, though the
selection there had a slant to carpet types and not always comparable with
last week's sharply dearer sale. The outstanding market of the week was the
auction of British wool in Bradford with prices 7.5% to 10% dearer, and also
at new seasonal peaks. All the pressure to rising prices seems to be coming
from primary markets and little pull from the retail end is indicated in the
trade. Australian offerings are higher than expected in the remaining weeks
of the season and a negligible amount of stockpile wool is to be added to
three auctions to test out this method of stockpile disposal, due to start
in the first half of the next season.
