<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / International Company News: Dairy Farm advances 11% despite
currency movement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE LUCAS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Dairy Farm International, the food retailing arm of Hong Kong's Jardine
Matheson group, yesterday reported an 11 per cent rise in net profits to
USDollars 197.5m for 1993, up from Dollars 177.8m the year before.
Mr Tim Westinghouse, finance director, said earnings were hit by currency
fluctuations, especially in Australia and the UK, combined with a
competitive retail climate and low inflation in many of the countries in
which the group operates. Nonetheless, the results were ahead of market
expectations.
Earnings per share climbed 4 per cent to 11.28 cents, following last year's
Dollars 202m rights issue of convertible preference shares. Shareholders
will receive a final dividend of 4.1 cents, up from 3.9 cents a year ago.
Profits before interest fell 15 per cent to Dollars 64.6m in Australia,
where the group operates 238 Franklins stores and three Big Fresh outlets,
partially due to the fall in currency but also because of increased
overheads prompted by Sunday trading and the move into Big Fresh.
Contributions from the UK, where Dairy Farm owns 29 per cent of Kwik Save,
were lifted by record earnings at the discount store; but the Spanish retail
chain Simago continued to make a loss. The chain, acquired in 1990, is
expected to turn into the black this year.
Asia produced Dollars 93.6m of profits before interest, with Wellcome
supermarkets in Taiwan making their first full-year profit. In Hong Kong,
the supermarkets performed satisfactorily in spite of spiralling wage and
rental costs.
Dairy Farm also announced its intention to buy up 'odd lots' of shares from
Hong Kong and Singapore small investors - some 30 per cent of the firm's
shareholders hold fewer than the 1,000 shares which make up a board lot - at
a 5 per cent premium to the market price: a move which could potentially
cost the group Dollars 1.8m if fully taken up. It affects just 0.06 per cent
of Dairy Farm's issued share capital.
</TEXT>
