<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / International Company News: Banco de Chile share trading
suspended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID PILLING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SANTIAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Banco de Chile, the country's largest private bank, yesterday became the
second company within a week to have trading in its shares suspended after
three shareholders filed an injunction against the board of directors.
The series A shareholders filed a 'recourse' with the Court of Appeal in an
effort to stop Banco de Chile issuing new shares to series B shareholders
instead of cash dividends.
Lawyers representing the three complainants claim the measure threatened
'fundamental constitutional rights' pertaining to property ownership.
The move would inevitably dilute the stake of series A shareholders, who own
9 per cent of the bank.
The Superintendencia, the country's banking watchdog, stopped all trading
for the rest of the week after Banco de Chile failed to overturn the
injunction.
</TEXT>
