<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / International Company News: ENI subsidiary sells gas side
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor and JOHN SIMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Agip Petroli, the refining and distribution subsidiary of ENI, the Italian
state-owned oil and gas group, has agreed to sell its Liquipibigas business
for the equivalent of Dollars 146m as part of its preparations for
privatisation.
The purchaser is Novogas, a Brescia-based joint venture between Primagaz of
France and Brixia Finanziara, a privately-owned Italian company in transport
and fuel distribution. The deal includes a 35 per cent interest in the
Livorno gas import terminal.
Liquipibigas, based in Milan, owns and operates the second-largest liquefied
petroleum gas distribution network in Italy with 25 storage and bottling
facilities. Its revenues last year were L359bn (Dollars 215m).
ENI is reshaping its energy interests into a new company which is due to be
privatised next year. Yesterday's sale, first announced last summer, was
conducted through an auction and is among the largest of ENI's disposals so
far of non-core businesses.
Novogas was advised by Merrill Lynch.
Great Lakes Chemical Corporation of the US has acquired the plastic
materials activities of EniChem Synthesis for L150bn, writes John Simkins in
Milan.
ENI's revenue from pri-vatisation now totals about L2,700bn, and the
businesses sold have a combined turnover of more than L4,000bn with a total
workforce of 11,000.
</TEXT>
