FT  18 MAR 94 / International Company News: Viacom hires Sony Pictures
executive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jonathan Dolgen, who has a reputation as one of Hollywood's shrewdest
deal-makers and toughest managers, is quitting Sony Pictures Entertainment
to head a new film and television entertainment group being formed by Viacom
following its Dollars 10bn takeover of Paramount Communications.
The appointment is a key one for Viacom, because Paramount's Hollywood
operations have had a lacklustre record in recent years, even though they
were the main prize in the recent bitter takeover battle for the company.
Viacom needs to improve sharply its results to justify the high price it
paid for the business.
Mr Dolgen's move, announced by Viacom yesterday, is a fresh blow to Sony
Pictures Entertainment, which owns the Columbia and Tristar studios and has
suffered in recent years from a very mixed box office record and
considerable senior management upheaval.
Mr Dolgen, 48, was president of Sony Pictures Entertainment's motion picture
group, where he had responsibility for the business side of the group,
rather than creative operations, and was renowned as a cost-cutter who
reined back its once lavish expenditure.
He has a reputation as an intimidating manager, with a confrontational
style: his office at Fox Inc, where he worked before joining Sony, was
nicknamed the 'house of pain and suffering'.
His move comes at a time when Japan's Sony, which paid Dollars 3.4bn for
Columbia in 1989, is exploring the possible sale of a minority stake in its
motion picture operations to a strategic investor, such as a telephone or
cable company.
Mr Dolgen will be chairman of Viacom Entertainment Group, which will oversee
Paramount's film and television business and incorporate Viacom's own
substantial television production, distribution and broadcasting operations.
</TEXT>
