<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Purchases help Baynes rise 48%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Contributions from acquisitions helped Charles Baynes, the distribution and
specialist engineering business, lift 1993 pre-tax profits by 48 per cent.
The group, which spent Pounds 48m on purchases during the year dominated by
Buck &amp; Hickman, the industrial tools distributor acquired for Pounds 33m
last autumn, said contributions from these operations pushed profits up from
Pounds 5.6m to Pounds 8.2m.
Sales advanced to Pounds 91.2m (Pounds 70.3m), including Pounds 27.2m from
acquisitions. The comparative figure included Pounds 5.68m from discontinued
activities. Continuing activities rose 41 per cent.
Acquisitions provided Pounds 2.56m of operating profits of Pounds 7.9m
(Pounds 4.1m). Profits from underlying businesses moved ahead 34 per cent to
Pounds 5.4m, despite a 1 per cent fall in turnover.
Earnings per share increased to 3.71p (2.8p), while a proposed final
dividend of 1.075p (0.9p) takes the total to 1.65p (1.425p).
Welcoming the figures, Mr John Perkins, finance director, said the group had
defied flat markets in the UK and continental Europe and increased operating
margins by embarking on a cost-cutting programme.
Aerospace engineering suffered the brunt of the rationalisation as the
workforce was cut by 25 per cent to 430 after six plants acquired from
Cookson Group were merged on one site.
'The aerospace business remains poor and we do not envisage a substantial
pick up before 1995,' according to Mr Perkins, who predicted further
rationalisation in the valves and packaging sectors.
He also hinted at fresh acquisitions, which would be financed from cash
reserves or debt rather than new equity.
COMMENT
With net cash of Pounds 10.1m, Baynes is well-placed to pick off small
engineering companies and has the support of its bankers to go for larger
prey. Its ability to do so has been enhanced considerably by stripping out
costs from existing businesses and making shrewd purchases at home and
abroad. Impressed by its strategy, analysts have upgraded profit forecasts
to Pounds 12.1m. Although the prospective multiple of 17.5 is ahead of the
sector average, the shares are worth considering given the group's record
for earnings enhancing deals.
</TEXT>
